    {
        "client_msg_id": "333F2303-414D-4B16-BE7C-24F3E553F859",
        "type": "message",
        "text": "Adding onto that, it’s not just an issue that affects the research community and collaborators, questionable research practices can also affect people’s lives or society more broadly. For example, when questionable research is publicized by questionable researchers, when it’s adopted by policy makers or organizations, or when it is memed into the cultural zeitgeist. And, as it currently stands, many researchers doing these things don’t face any consequences.\n\nIf you look at the history of research ethics law in Canada (which have only been around ~24 years), I think there’s precedent that these practices should have formal investigations and consequences depending on the circumstances.",
        "user": "U01AA7U4UHY",
        "ts": "1603850196.016300",
